| Notes                   = * One of the world's most popular characters is back on the big screen as a new chapter in the Spider-Man legacy is revealed in The Amazing Spider-Man. Focusing on an untold story that tells a different side of the Peter Parker story, the new film's stars Andrew Garfield, Emma Stone, Rhys Ifans, Denis Leary, Campbell Scott, Irrfan Khan, with Martin Sheen and Sally Field. The film is directed by Marc Webb from a screenplay written by James Vanderbilt, based on the Marvel Comic Book by Stan Lee and Steve Ditko. Laura Ziskin, Avi Arad, and Matt Tolmach are producing the film in association with Marvel Entertainment for Columbia Pictures, which opened in theaters everywhere in 2D and 3D on July 3, 2012.
| Trivia                  = *Due to disagreements on ''Spider-Man 4'', Sam Raimi and Tobey Maguire dropped out of the film. Sony had already made a backup plan just in case this happened. James Vanderbilt wrote the reboot at the same time of Raimi's writing of ''Spider-Man 4''.
*The name Spider-Man is only heard eight times throughout the entire movie. Three of those times are spoken by Captain George Stacy. No other character, not even Spider-Man himself, speaks the name more than once.
*[[Brian Michael Bendis]], author of '''Ultimate Spider-Man''' had been asked to help write the script of the movie, and was confirmed this through his twitter account.
* In 2011, Sony reached an agreement with Walt Disney Motion Pictures which would incorporate the OsCorp Tower of ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' into Disney's release ''[[Marvel's The Avengers]]'', but the New York skyline of said film had already finished rendering before OsCorp Tower had been designed. Despite this alleged attempt at a tie-in, the ''Amazing Spider-Man'' franchise is not considered part of the ''[[Earth-199999|Marvel Cinematic Universe]]'' franchise and does not share continuity with ''The Avengers'' or its subsequent releases by Marvel Studios.
*In 2010, a campaign with the hashtag "#donald4spiderman" went viral, pushing for having [[wikipedia:Donald Glover|Donald Glover]] as Peter Parker in the upcoming movie, but he didn't get the chance to audition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-spider-man-homecoming-donald-glover-20170706-story.html|title=How Donald Glover wound up in ‘Spider-Man: Homecoming,’ and what it might mean for an inclusive future|author=Jen Yamato|work=Los Angeles Times |date=6 July 2017|accessdate=13 June 2020}}</ref>
*In June 2012, to promote the film, Marvel and Wal-Mart released a special preview pack consisting of a DVD with behind the scenes videos, trailers and movie clips, and a reprinting of {{cl|Amazing Spider-Man Vol 1 6}}, the first appearance of the mainstream [[Curtis Connors (Earth-616)|Lizard]].
*The viral website [http://thedailybugle.tumblr.com/ ''The Daily Bugle'' on Tumblr] gives the date of the film's events as occurring in July [[:Category:2013|2013]] (according to [[John Jonah Jameson (Earth-120703)|J. Jonah Jameson]], the events occurred three months before his editorial of October 30, 2013).
*The video game [[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 video game)]], apparently takes place only months after the film. However, it is believed to be non-canon in the Amazing Spider-Man universe.
*In the comics, Gwen Stacy was an only child living with her widowed father. In the movie, her mother is alive and she has three younger brothers - Howard, Philip, and Simon.
* This continuity was set to still have a Sinister Six movie and a third and fourth film of Spider-Man but those plans were cancelled due to Sony's deal with Disney.
** In an interview, the director Marc Webb reveals what those movies could have been.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/08/09/amazing-spider-man-3-plot-marc-webb-andrew-garfield/|title=Amazing Spider-Man 3: Director reveals scrapped plans for Andrew Garfield sequel|author=Nick Romano|work=EW (Entertainment Weekly)|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>

